import duckdb
import pandas as pd

url = "https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/iris/iris.data"
column_names = ['sepal_length', 'sepal_width', 'petal_length', 'petal_width', 'class']
df = pd.read_csv(url, header=None, names=column_names)

con = duckdb.connect(database=':memory:')
con.execute("CREATE TABLE iris AS SELECT * FROM df")

# Plotting boxplots to identify outliers visually and explain why they are considered outliers
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

plt.figure(figsize=(14, 8))
for i, column in enumerate(df.columns[:-1], 1):
    plt.subplot(2, 2, i)
    sns.boxplot(y=df[column])
    plt.title(f'Box plot of {column}')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Using IQR method to find outliers and add reasons
def find_outliers_IQR_with_reason(data):
    outliers_with_reason = pd.DataFrame(columns=data.columns)
    for col in data.columns[:-1]:  # exclude the class column
        Q1 = data[col].quantile(0.25)
        Q3 = data[col].quantile(0.75)
        IQR = Q3 - Q1
        lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
        upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
        outliers_col = data[(data[col] < lower_bound) | (data[col] > upper_bound)]
        reasons = []
        for index, row in outliers_col.iterrows():
            value = row[col]
            if value < lower_bound:
                reason = f'{col} < {lower_bound}'
            elif value > upper_bound:
                reason = f'{col} > {upper_bound}'
            reasons.append(reason)
        if not outliers_col.empty:
            outliers_col['reason'] = reasons
            outliers_with_reason = pd.concat([outliers_with_reason, outliers_col])
    return outliers_with_reason

outliers_with_reason = find_outliers_IQR_with_reason(df)
outliers_with_reason
